Suppose I have a linear transformation given by the following matrix:
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
2 & 3 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\]
My first question is, does this apply to any vector except for the zero vector?

Second question, if \[
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
1 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\] is multiplied by the matrix above, what is the relationship between the two rows?
Let's address your questions one by one. The matrix you provided represents a linear transformation, but it doesn't apply to the zero vector. The zero vector (0,0) is always mapped to itself under any linear transformation, but that's a trivial case.

Regarding your second question, when you multiply the vector \[
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
1 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\] by the matrix, you get:
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
2 & 3 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
1 \\
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
2 \\
5 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\]
This shows the result of the transformation.

To understand the relationship between the two rows after the transformation, let's apply the transformation to the second vector: \[
\begin{bmatrix}
2 \\
3 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\]
This results in the vector \[
\begin{bmatrix}
5 \\
11 \\
\end{bmatrix}
\]
